{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655208"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:01:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:01:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18658"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18658"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11390"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116539"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11390"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18658"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98532"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7244"},{"type":"tags","id":"7248"},{"type":"tags","id":"7258"},{"type":"tags","id":"7573"},{"type":"tags","id":"11241"},{"type":"tags","id":"11377"},{"type":"tags","id":"11378"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"50122"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116539"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe midsagittal view of the skull reveals important anatomical landmarks of the cranial fossae and the bones that form them.\u003Cbr\u003EOne key structure is the sella turcica, which houses the pituitary gland.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the location of the sella turcica?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior to the ethmoid bone","Lateral to the temporal bone","Within the posterior cranial fossa","Posterior to the cribriform plate","Posterior to the occipital bone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sella turcica is a midline, saddle-shaped depression in the body of the sphenoid bone that contains the pituitary gland. It lies in the middle cranial fossa. Relative to the ethmoid bone, particularly its cribriform plate which forms the anterior cranial fossa floor, the sella turcica is located posteriorly. Therefore, \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior to the cribriform plate\u003C/strong\u003E best describes its location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior to the ethmoid bone\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the ethmoid, including the cribriform plate, is anterior to the sphenoid; the sella turcica is posterior to it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral to the temporal bone\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the sella turcica is a midline structure within the sphenoid, not lateral to the temporal bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithin the posterior cranial fossa\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the sella turcica is in the middle cranial fossa, bounded posteriorly by the dorsum sellae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior to the occipital bone\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; the occipital bone forms the posterior skull, so the sella turcica cannot be posterior to it.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The sella turcica is a saddle-shaped depression in the sphenoid bone containing the pituitary gland.","The sella turcica lies in the middle cranial fossa posterior to the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u0022Sella turcica\u0022 by BodyParts3D is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 2.1 jp Unported license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.1/jp/deed.en). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Sella_turcica01.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98532"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18658"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21429"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21429"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Mc25FiXtngC6BnXWCr3dTGGHdTIIUL.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Mc25FiXtngC6BnXWCr3dTGGHdTIIUL.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":640}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98532"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T18:58:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-30T14:16:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11390"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116539"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":